"An alternative would be to embed the Scipy function and write a thin wrapper around it, but I don't know if licenses allow it. Pyminuit is GPL, so definitely not compatible.\n\n\nImplementing Scan is not that hard it will just wrap around Minuit's scan. If you want to give it a try see migrad in the pyx file.\n\n\nOh... PyMinuit Scan is not Minuit Scan. Still it's not hard to write and see migrad if you want to make one.\n\n\n@Dapid Do you want to give this a try?\n\n\nI can give it a try.\n\nI think the best approach is to use Scipy if it is present, with a fallback to a home cooked version if not. I will see how they do it.\n\n\nI'd prefer `iminuit` stay independent from `scipy`.\n\nAs long as it's pure-python code like `scipy/optimize/optimize.py` we can just bundle a copy in `iminuit/extern/scipy_optimize.py` though  ... no need to spend time re-coding what's there already.\n\nhttps://github.com/scipy/scipy/blob/v0.14.0/scipy/optimize/optimize.py#L2374\n\n\nI also needed the PyMinuit scan function and found it missing from iminuit. I don't know if you have something smarter in mind, but here is a quick thing that I cooked up to do that job. First, a generator function to produce iterable N-dimension grid points using the arg format that scan() used:\n\n```\ndef scangrid(*args, **kwargs):\n    \"\"\"\n    Generator function which returns lists of parameter (name, value)\n    2-tuples via yields (i.e. in a for-expression).\n\n    The arguments are 4-tuples of (name, numpts, low, high) for each\n    parameter; the generator iterations will then visit each of the\n    lattice points in a grid with num points between low..high in each\n    param.\n    \"\"\"\n    vec = kwargs.get(\"vec\", [])\n    if args:\n        # print \"@\", len(args) #, args\n        var, npts, low, high = args[0]\n        for val in np.linspace(low, high, npts):\n            newargs = args[1:]\n            newvec = vec + [(var, val)]\n            newkwargs = kwargs\n            newkwargs[\"vec\"] = newvec\n            for i in scangrid(*newargs, **newkwargs):\n                yield i\n            # TODO: in Python3 this can replace the extra for-loop above\n            # yield from scan(*newargs, **newkwargs):\n    else:\n        yield vec\n```\n\nAnd then an example of it being used to find a brute force minimum:\n\n```\ndef fcn(a,b,c):\n    \"Some function, i.e. Minuit.fcn\"\n    return a**2 + b**2 + c**2\n\n# Find the minimum value of fcn(x) in the grid. Can maybe be done in cool one-liner ways\nscanbest = (None, None)\ngen = scangrid((\"a\", nscan, amin, amax), (\"b\", nscan, bmin, bmax), (\"c\", nscan, cmin, cmax))\nfor p in gen:\n    x = fcn(**dict(p))\n    if scanbest[1] is None or x < scanbest[1]:\n        scanbest = (p, x)\n\nprint \"BEST FROM SCAN = \", scanbest\n```\n\nFrom this, dict(scanbest[0]) can be used as starting point arg to the iminuit.Minuit constructor. Seems to work. This could all be bundled into a new method on Minuit if you wanted -- I didn't do it that way since it needs to be done in the Cython definition of the Minuit class, rather than be \"appended\" to it as a post-hoc method.\n\nIs this any use? It'd be nice to not have to copy this code around to every place where I need to do a simple grid scan before gradient descent!\n\n\nI think @agbuckley volunteered to contribute this feature to iminuit.\n\n@piti118 - Could you please have a look at his last comment and say if you want this in iminuit and give feedback on API / implementation?\n\n\nRemoving v1.3 milestone. Not many users will use this, and there's no PR, so it shouldn't hold up a release given that we have a ton of good new stuff thanks to @HDembinski ."